For the planning system to work, local communities need a level playing field
If local communities are to have faith in the planning system, then the system needs to recognise that there needs to be a much stronger local voice than currently exists, writes Chris Skidmore
Mr Boles says the projections for the households being created in this country were 'terrifying' Photo: Paul Grover for the Telegraph	By Chris Skidmore
2:11PM GMT 10 Jan 2013
Comments
Planning Minister Nick Boles’ speech at Policy Exchange set out a vision in which communities will have greater control and benefit over development in their neighbourhoods. In the minister’s speech was also the welcome and extremely important distinction, too frequently ignored, between ‘green belt’ land and green field land. There are only fourteen areas of green belt in the country, a total of 1,639,540 hectares, forming just 13 per cent of the countryside. If only 8 per cent of all land has been developed on, then there is clearly an argument that the Green Belt land can be preserved while at the same time finding room to build the necessary number of houses on green field for future generations. Green Belt land, having been given strengthened protected status in the National Planning Policy Framework, remains protected — something that the previous government’s Regional Spatial Strategies planned to remove in order to allow mass building on the Green Belt. Nick Boles has rightly made the consistent commitment that the Green Belt will be protected and ministers should continually remind people of this vital distinction. Equally, just as politicians should be careful not to demonise those unfortunate enough to find themselves in circumstances where they have to claim welfare as scroungers, we should caution against the cat calls of NIMBY for anyone concerned about the future of their local area and neighbourhood. What concerns people is not so much that there should be no housing at all, but that new houses should not be, in the words of the minister, "ugly rubbish", but beautiful and sensitive to their surroundings. While we must ensure that there are many thousands more homes for future generations to build secure lives of their own, we have a duty also to protect and conserve areas of natural beauty. This does not have to be exclusively reserved for the countryside, as former Tourism minister John Penrose has effectively pointed out; urban views of architectural significance and beauty have equal right to be retained for the future. Many local groups have already been working closely with local authorities to ensure that Core Strategies are put in place to determine the long term future of their areas, and today’s speech will encourage many that they will be added incentives for doing so. Yet there remains persistent problem that local communities can never be fully empowered when the planning system remains tilted in favour of developers who have a right to appeal planning decisions that go against them, when residents have none. According to recent Government statistics, in the last decade 8,663 planning applications were granted despite having significantly cut across agreed development plans. Although these are just 0.15 per cent of the six million submitted in this period, these figures only include applications for development large enough to have been referred to the Secretary of State. The problem is exacerbated when local authorities, the supposed democratic guardians of the planning process, are press ganged into accepting developments in fear of legal challenges that they cannot afford to defend. Recently, I introduced a 10 minute rule bill into Parliament calling for a Community Right of Appeal that would help level the playing field: local communities would be able to challenge a development contrary to local neighbourhood plans by proving that a significant proportion of the neighbourhood were strongly opposed to an application being passed in the form of a petition. This would reflect a certain proportion of a local ward, say 25 per cent of the electorate, which would trigger a right of appeal. This is hardly a new concept: a community right of appeal exists in Australia, for instance, and has had little impact on growth while at the same time ensures public confidence in the planning process. The introduction of such a community right of appeal was also a pre-election pledge both in the 2010 Conservative Party Green Paper Open Source Planning that talked of creating a ‘symmetrical’ planning structure and in the 2010 Liberal Democrat General Election Manifesto. Related Articles
Why I've been fighting so hard to save my home town
08 Mar 2013
Planning threat to grandparents
10 Jan 2013
I was a ‘Nimby’ once, planning minister tells Telegraph
10 Jan 2013
Sir Andrew Motion: blight of pylons will spoil every rural view in England
04 Jan 2013
If local communities are to have faith in the planning system, rather than it being a top-down process in which neighbourhoods feel that they have no control of the developments forced upon them, then the system needs to recognise that there needs to be a much stronger local voice than currently exists. Chris Skidmore is the MP for Kingswood Comment
