M&S data breach: Five ways to beat phishing emails
Marks and Spencer has warned customers to be on the look out for bogus emails after a database was stolen by hackers. Here are five ways to beat the fraudsters There is a lax attitude from many businesses when it comes to prioritising cyber security Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Christopher Williams, Technology Correspondent
1:36PM BST 07 Apr 2011
Comments
Marks and Spencer is one of more than a dozen major brands affected by the theft of data held by Epsilon, an email marketing company based in Texas. The data is limited to email addresses and names, but criminals could use it in to trick more valuable information such as passwords from victims - a type of internet fraud known as "phishing". Internet security experts expects a spate of phishing attacks on the millions of individuals whose data was stolen from Epsilon in coming weeks. But there is no reason to be caught out: 1. Beware forgeries
Criminals can easily spoof the "From" field in emails, so if a message says it comes from customerservice@marksandspencer.com, that does not mean it really does. Related Articles
