2. Suspect links
Phishing emails often encourage their targets to click on links to counterfeit websites that will then ask for valuable data. Savvy internet users don't click on links in unsolicited emails. 3. Inspect the URL
If you do click on links in emails check that the URL in your browser's address bar is what you expected. Check carefully, as criminals could obtain a web address that is only very slightly different from the legitimate Marks and Spencer website. 4. Check for encryption
Legitimate e-commerce websites use encryption to ensure your sensitive data cannot be intercepted. If a website asks you for data and your browser does not show a padlock symbol it may be a phishing attempt. Genuine websites that ask for financial information should also turn the address bar green in more recent browsers. 5. Never download Exercise extreme caution if a website you have visited from an email asks you to download anything. Some phishing attacks are designed to distribute computer viruses that will directly steal your banking information. Criminals can trick victims into downloading by disguising them as legitimate files. Internet
